# Partition sizing — the unit of parallelism

## One partition = one task = one core

- The partition count **is** your parallelism — wrong in either direction hurts:
- **Too few** — idle cores, one slow task stalls the stage, OOM risk on a huge partition
- **Too many** — scheduling overhead dominates; tiny tasks cost more to set up than to run

## Rules of thumb

- **Cluster** — **128–256 MB per partition**
- **Local** — **2–4× CPU cores**
- **After a shuffle** — `spark.sql.shuffle.partitions` (default 200 → next)

Inspect: `df.rdd.getNumPartitions()` · `spark_partition_id()`
